Below is a Python simulation of satellite-derived Atmospheric Motion Vectors (AMVs) inspired by the MTSAT/JMA workflow. It is a teaching/demo model, not the full operational JMA system.

JMA’s MTSAT AMVs were derived from three successive images, and operationally included IR, VIS, WV, and SWIR AMVs from corresponding bands. MTSAT-1R began operations in 2005, and JMA later switched operational production to MTSAT-2, with hourly dissemination introduced around 2009–2010.

This simulation does four things:

    creates synthetic “cloud” imagery,

    advects it with a known wind field,

    estimates motion by block matching between frames,

    plots the recovered AMVs over the image.

import numpy as np
